 even a decade ago, would have deemed it as people not being able to make up their minds – just like bisexuals – but change is coming and The Art of Being Normal is evidence of that change.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"58f1c171d74ef893609d822b1f2c590edb02b24a\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/58f1c171d74ef893609d822b1f2c590edb02b24a/0_0_315_475/315.jpg\" alt=\"The Art of Being Normal\" width=\"315\" height=\"475\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"></span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>Leo Denton is the new boy in school. There is a rumour that he murdered someone with a hacksaw, and then he got expelled. Now a popular girl is interested in him, and Leo likes her too, but when you used to be Megan Denton, not everything is simple.</p> <p>David is your garden variety high–school outcast. With his best friends, they lead a pretty normal life. Except for the fact that David abhors the body he was born in; except for the fact that David wants to be a girl.</p> <p>This is not a love story. This is a story of acceptance, of coming out and of transition. It’s about learning to accept yourself, and about standing up for yourself when you need to. It’s about coming out to everyone who used to think of you as someone else altogether and then actually looking in the mirror and getting used to what you look like now! </p> <p>While I was reading about how covers of books with these powerful messages don’t have to be so obvious, and how stories are being released in which the transition isn’t the main element, I felt a little disconnected from The Art Of Being Normal. It was a good story, a GREAT story, it just didn’t make me feel much.</p> <p>Not the friendship between Leo and David, not the blossoming love between Alicia and Leo, or even that intense need to transform yourself to another gender, all of which I would have expected to find, and I was a tad disappointed!</p> <p>And yet, if it wasn’t clear enough already, I respect this book and everything it stands for. I loved the idea of the characters, the idea of their friendship, their family lives, their friends, even how they realised that there would always be people that belittled them for who they are, but together they could make it– just not the execution of these ideas.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/childrens-books/2011/mar/02/how-do-i-get-involved-guardian-childrens-books\">How do I get involved in the Guardian children's books site?</a> </p> </aside>  <p>I don’t think I’ve done this justice, but that’s all I can think of saying for now!</p> <ul> <li><strong>Buy this book at the <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/360861/\">Guardian Bookshop</a></strong></li> </ul> <h2><strong>Want to tell the world about a book you’ve read? <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/childrens-books/2011/mar/02/how-do-i-get-involved-guardian-childrens-books\">Join the site</a> and send us your review!</strong></h2>","liveBloggingNow":"false","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4gahn","wordcount":"568","standfirst":"<p>‘This is a story of acceptance, of coming out and of transition’</p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2016/feb/12/the-art-of-being-normal-lisa-williamson-review","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/childrens-books-site/2016/feb/12/the-art-of-being-normal-lisa-williamson-review","sectionName":"Children's books","elements":[{"id":"58f1c171d74ef893609d822b1f2c590edb02b24a","relation":"body","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/58f1c171d74ef893609d822b1f2c590edb02b24a/0_0_315_475/315.jpg","typeData":{"role":"thumbnail","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/58f1c171d74ef893609d822b1f2c590edb02b24a","altText":"The Art of Being Normal","caption":"","source":"PR","credit":"Photograph: PR"