owling? When she collaborates","sectionId":"books","type":"article","rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"id":"books/2016/feb/12/when-is-jk-rowling-not-jk-rowling-when-she-collaborates-harry-potter-cursed-child","fields":{"commentable":"true","byline":"Claire Armitstead","headline":"When is JK Rowling not JK Rowling? When she collaborates","trailText":"Fans disappointed that the words of Harry Potter and the Cursed Child will be scripted by Jack Thorne haven’t quite understood how playwriting works","hasStoryPackage":"false","productionOffice":"UK","body":"<p>JK Rowling caused a ripple of dismay on social media on Thursday when she confirmed that the script for the forthcoming Harry Potter play, which is to be published as a book in July, was not strictly-speaking written by her.</p> <p>Publicity for Harry Potter and the Cursed Child Parts I and II featured a picture of Rowling, pen in hand, poring over the script with the director and scriptwriter, inviting the assumption that it was her own work. That assumption was bolstered by the announcement that the book would be the eighth official Harry Potter title, prompting jubilation from Waterstones chief James Daunt, who crowed that there were “no sweeter three words to the ears of a bookseller than ‘the eighth story’.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/feb/10/new-harry-potter-cursed-child-eighth-book-july-play-script\">New Harry Potter book from JK Rowling coming out in July: the play script</a> </p> </aside>  <p>Within 24 hours of the announcement that the script would be released as a book in a global publishing deal involving the UK, the US and Australia, it had soared to No 1 in book charts.</p> <p>It took a perplexed fan to clarify the situation. Victoria Green tweeted JK Rowling to say that she had bet her teacher that Rowling would “‘not write, publish, or announce another novel about Harry Potter before May 1 2017’, who wins? Only you can decide.”</p> <p>While the marketers of the book may have been being economical with the <em>actualité</em>, Rowling was happy to set things straight, replying: “You win! <a href=\"https://twitter.com/hashtag/CursedChild?src=hash\">#CursedChild</a> is a play and while we have worked very closely on it, the wonderful writer is <a href=\"https://twitter.com/jackthorne\">@jackthorne</a>.”<br /></p>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/gillyweedgreen/status/697947857832255490\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"https://twitter.com/jk_rowling\">@jk_rowling</a> My chemistry teacher &amp; I have a 2011 bet to settle. With &quot;Cursed Child,&quot; who wins? Only you can decide. <a href=\"https://t.co/2QBzyKRDDa\">pic.twitter.com/2QBzyKRDDa</a></p>&mdash; τσri (@gillyweedgreen) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/gillyweedgreen/status/697947857832255490\">February 12, 2016</a></blockquote>  </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/jk_rowling/status/698046788348088320\">  <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\">You win! <a href=\"https://twitter.com/hashtag/CursedChild?src=hash\">#CursedChild</a> is a play and while we have worked very closely on it, the wonderful writer is <a href=\"https://twitter.com/jackthorne\">@jackthorne</a>  <a href=\"https://t.co/MpM5zMoiJN\">https://t.co/MpM5zMoiJN</a></p>&mdash; J.K. Rowling (@jk_rowling) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/jk_rowling/status/698046788348088320\">February 12, 2016</a></blockquote>  </figure>  <p>What Rowling’s own Pottermore site said was a masterclass in the dark arts of fudging: “The play opens in London’s West End this summer, based on an original new story by JK Rowling, Jack Thorne and John Tiffany. It is officially the eighth story in Harry Potter canon and a new play by Jack Thorne.”<br /></p> <p>Whoever penned the words on the page, it’s unlikely that Amazon will seeing a slew of cancelled orders, but the confusion does cast light on the delicate issue of collaboration and authorship, which is at its most complicated in scripts for stage or screen.</p> <p>Viewed by Harry Potter diehards, desperate for a new book, the picture of Rowling flanked by director John Tiffany and writer Jack Thorne might indeed seem misleading, but in the context of a stage play, it is a truthful representation of a collaboration in which director and scriptwriter are serving the author’s vision, taking notes from her and filtering them through the lens of their own crafts.<br /></p> <p>In a sense it’s an inversion of the writer-editor relationship in books, with Rowling wielding the blue pencil over the scriptwriter’s work. The resulting script may not be all her own work, but it won’t anyway be a complete work of literature in the sense that an original Harry Potter novel would be.<br /></p> <p>And that may be the real story of Harry Potter and the Cursed Child. Not many people read play scripts for fun, for the very good reason that they are created to be performed. For the Potter fans who queue up for the latest midnight release, this realisation may be a rude awakening. Not for nothing does Rowling’s own <a href=\"https://www.pottermore.com/news/ww-publishing-cursed-child-script-book-announcement\">Pottermore website describe it</a> as “a Special Rehearsal Edition of the script book of new stage play”.<br /></p>","liveBloggingNow":"false","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4gk38","wordcount":"549","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/2e3897438eaaa8993191bff872c50886a06d3101/0_99_1772_1064/140.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2016-02-19T00:00:00Z","standfirst":"<p>Fans disappointed that the words of Harry Potter and the Cursed Child will be scripted by Jack Thorne haven’t quite understood how playwriting works</p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/feb/12/when-is-jk-rowling-not-jk-rowling-when-she-collaborates-har