tage illustrator for an improvised musical-comedy show! <br><br>The judges commented her on “well-observed, figurative drawing, good gestures and expressions.” So well done Andrea!</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Illustration: Andrea Ipaktchi</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"bc5cf374a6a15344f9cfcb487542004a28addb96\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/bc5cf374a6a15344f9cfcb487542004a28addb96/0_0_651_1000/651.jpg\" alt=\"Bring Your Pet to School Day\" width=\"651\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">This gorgeous illustration by Portia Rosenberg is called Bring Your Pet to School Day, it’s also a response to the illustration prompt: (Cinder) Ella Grubb and the School for Princesses (which seems to have been a popular choice for the winning illustrators). <br><br>Portia loves drawing, especially faces – and loves depicting character and liveliness. Judges praised her use of “characterisation and expression”.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Illustration: Portia Rosenberg</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"bca018405149f0d7a792d1d030547d31f9025016\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/bca018405149f0d7a792d1d030547d31f9025016/0_0_1000_1535/651.jpg\" alt=\"The fast way up\" width=\"651\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Here’s Mary Hays’ The Fast Way Up. It’s a response to the illustration prompt: Jack and the Tower Block. Mary loves finding ways to visually express feelings and ideas present in stories written for older children (and adults). <br><br>Praise from the judges focused on her “great textural work” and the way the “composition means that the audience can put themselves in the picture.”</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Illustration: Mary Hays</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-im