":"type/article","webTitle":"Article","type":"type","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]},{"id":"profile/teju-cole","webTitle":"Teju Cole","r2ContributorId":"49358","firstName":"teju","lastName":"cole","type":"contributor","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/teju-cole","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/profile/teju-cole","references":[]},{"id":"publication/theguardian","webTitle":"The Guardian","type":"publication","sectionId":"theguardian","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/all","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/publication/theguardian","sectionName":"From the Guardian","references":[]},{"id":"theguardian/guardianreview","webTitle":"Guardian review","type":"newspaper-book","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/guardianreview","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/theguardian/guardianreview","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"theguardian/guardianreview/saturdayreviewsfeatres","webTitle":"Features & reviews","type":"newspaper-book-section","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/guardianreview/saturdayreviewsfeatres","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/theguardian/guardianreview/saturdayreviewsfeatres","sectionName":"Books","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"webPublicationDate":"2016-02-12T09:30:15Z","webTitle":"The Spaces in Between by Caroline Jones review – the secret misery of an eating disorder","sectionId":"books","type":"article","rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"id":"books/2016/feb/12/the-spaces-in-between-caroline-jones-review-memoir","fields":{"commentable":"true","byline":"Alice O'Keeffe","headline":"The Spaces in Between by Caroline Jones review – the secret misery of an eating disorder","trailText":"Beneath the calm surface of a high-achieving and eventful life flowed strong and deadly currents – described in this subtle memoir","hasStoryPackage":"false","productionOffice":"UK","body":"<p>By the age of 31, Caroline Jones appeared to be the very definition of a stable and high-achieving woman. She was a documentary producer at the BBC, and her latest film, about <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/society/alzheimers\" title=\"\">Alzheimer’s disease</a>, was nominated for a prestigious award. She had an Oxford degree and a flat in London, and had never had any trouble attracting boyfriends, nor maintaining stable relationships.</p> <p>But beneath the calm surface of her life flowed strong and deadly currents. When she was a teenager at boarding school a fellow student had showed her how to binge on food, and then throw it up afterwards. The habit, which she soon recognised as the eating disorder <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/society/bulimia\" title=\"\">bulimia</a>, became a psychological crutch, a way of managing “strange, leaking-out” feelings. The messiness – both physical and emotional – is kept locked away behind the bathroom door; the symptoms are apparent only to those who know where to look (“They think they’ve cleaned it up,” complains a cleaner at the school of the constantly vomit-flecked toilets, “but they always miss a bit right under the rim, so we know they’ve been doing it”).</p> <p>Tidily, considerately, avoiding any panic or fuss, Jones concealed the extent of her illness from everyone, even her closest family, for 14 years. On bad days at Oxford, she would shut her curtains and cram down bagfuls of cream cakes, custard, biscuits and chocolate. After vomiting, she would place all the wrappers carefully in the bin and tidy her room; by the time she opened the curtains again everything was perfectly spick and span. There were moments when the chaos threatened to spill out – she was arrested after shoplifting cream cakes for a binge – but she smartly talked her way out of trouble, both with the police and the university authorities. She graduated with a good degree.</p> <p>At the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/media/bbc\" title=\"\">BBC</a>, she would sometimes start to binge before she had even left the office. “Nobody notices if I lift out one chocolate bar after another, one biscuit at a time, head down, working, diligent.” It felt good to let go, to take off her respectable mask and reveal a chaotic, greedy monster, gorging itself on sweet, sticky, garishly coloured food. It would only be later, purged and sore in the privacy of her flat, that she looked in the mirror and despaired.</p> <p>Eating disorders can seem bizarre, even infuriating, to people fortunate enough never to have suffered from one. Perhaps this is why they remain largely cloaked in shame and silence, while literature abounds with tales of drug and alcohol addiction. Drugs and alcohol are – superficially, of course – more fun. They allow addicts not only to lose control, but to absolve themselves of responsibility for damage caused while under the influence. And addiction can be explained away as a physical dependence, while there is no getting around the fact that the roots of an eating disorder are emotional. Surely, the teenage Jones admonished herself, all she needed to do was find the “strength, self discipline … and the sense, the simple bloody sense, to change things”?</p> <p>Jones did eventually recover during her early 30s, thanks to a therapist at a specialist eating disorder unit. <em>The Spaces in Between</em> is her attempt to unearth the roots of her bulimia, and to explain why strength and self-discipline were not the answer – in fact, they may have been part of the problem. The story that emerges is both fascinating and complex, drawing together Jones’s personal experience and the wider sickness of the world we all live in.</p> <p>Throughout Jones’s childhood her parents were aid workers, and the family moved so many times that she has to include a chronology at the beginning showing their progress from Ethiopia to Lesotho to Kenya to Sudan to Pakistan. It was, in many ways, a privileged existence: they had gardeners and housekeepers, went to private schools, spent holidays camping in game parks and swimming in lakes and oceans. But while they were kept in relative luxury, the family were also intimately involved with the world at its cruellest and most miserable. Her father coordinated medical relief teams for the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/international-committee-of-the-red-cross-icrc\" title=\"\">Red Cross</a> during the Biafran war; later he was responsible for getting food to refugees from Rwanda, and to Ugandans fleeing the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/mar/08/joseph-kony-lords-resistance-army\" title=\"\">Lord’s Resistance Army</a>. At times, the chaos surrounding them touched Jones personally – she was sent away to boarding school after Iraqi forces under Saddam Hussein invaded Kuwait and her school in Pakistan was closed for security reasons – but mainly it formed a backdrop, and served as a constant reminder of how lucky she was, how little grounds she had for feeling sorry for herself.</p> <p>Except that nobody can be perfectly happy all the time, and Jones certainly wasn’t when she arrived at boarding school, in the unfamiliar grey and cold of an English winter, leaving her parents and her bright, exotic life behind. She was convinced that her sadness revealed her to be a terrible, ungrateful person, and set about secretly proving this to herself again and again. The irony of her father alleviating famine on one side of the world and his daughter gorging herself on the other is almost too obvious, and Jones is too subtle a writer to labour it directly. But she does tell us that the key to her recovery was finding compassion, not only for those worse off, but “compassion for myself”.</p> <p>• To order<strong> </strong><em>The Spaces in Between</em><strong> </strong>for £16 (RRP £20) go to <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/368040/s/the-spaces-in-between//?utm_source=editoriallink&amp;utm_medium=merch&amp;utm_campaign=article\" title=\"\">bookshop.theguardian.com</a> or call 0330 333 6846. Free UK p&amp;p over £10, online orders only.</p>","liveBloggingNow":"false","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4gvxx","wordcount":"962","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/2855ca232413846ad1e9153f4cc0725f502f0701/0_36_985_591/140.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2016-03-25T15:14:00Z","standfirst":"<p>Beneath the calm surface of a high-achieving and eventful life flowed strong and deadly currents – described in this subtle memoir</p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/feb/12/the-spaces-in-between-caroline-jones-review-memoir","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/2016/feb/12/the-spaces-in-between-caroline-jones-review-memoir","sectionName":"Books","elements":[{"id":"2855ca232413846ad1e9153f4cc0725f502f0701","relation":"main","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/2855ca232413846ad1e9153f4cc0725f502f0701/0_36_985_591/500.jpg","typeData":{"mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/2855ca232413846ad1e9153f4cc0725f502f0701","altText":"Caroline Jones","caption":"Caroline Jones hid her illness for 14 years","photographer":"PR Image","source":"PR Image","credit":"Photograph: PR Image","mediaId":"2855ca232413846ad1e9153f4cc0725f502f0701","displayCredit":"false","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/2855ca232413846ad1e9153f4cc0725f502f0701/0_36_985_591/500.jpg","width":"500","height":"300"},"mimeType":"image/jpeg"},{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/2855ca232413846ad1e9153f4cc0725f502f0701/0_36_985_591/140.jpg","typeData":{"mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/2855ca232413846ad1e9153f4cc0725f502f0701","altText":"Caroline Jones","caption":"Caroline Jones hid her illness for 14 years","photographer":"PR Image","source":"PR Image","credit":"Photograph: PR Image","mediaId":"2855ca232413846ad1e9153f4cc0725f502f0701","displayCred