<p>The Epic book of Epicness is a book about everything, full of amazing facts that you wouldn’t find in other fact books.</p> <p>A few of my favourite pages include ones about: the height of a guinea pig’s tooth if it grew for 14 years; how to cook an ostrich egg; a red waterfall in Antarctica; and how amazing the water bear is. </p> <p>One of the best things about this book is that there are facts about so many different things: animals, food, weather etc. There are funny facts, such as what noises animals make in different languages; disgusting facts, such as how much snot you swallow; and sad facts, such as how few tigers there are left in the world. Open any page and you will find something fascinating.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"dddc12eef60eb7d6b5790a46a54313a953750c85\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/dddc12eef60eb7d6b5790a46a54313a953750c85/0_0_325_499/325.jpg\" alt=\"The Epic Book of Epicness\" width=\"325\" height=\"499\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"></span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>The facts are presented with fun drawings so it should really be called ‘epic pictures’. The good thing about the pictures is that it makes the book easier to share with other people, like my little sister. They make it really easy to understand these amazingly epic facts.</p> <p>I would recommend this book to anyone who likes learning new things and I can’t wait to tell my friends some of the strange new facts I’ve discovered.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/childrens-books/2011/mar/02/how-do-i-get-involved-guardian-childrens-books\">How do I get involved in the Guardian children's books site?</a> </p> </aside>  <ul> <li><strong>Buy this book at the <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/325546/\">Guardian Bookshop</a></strong></li> </ul> <h2><